## USD/JPY 2026 Projection

While the USD/JPY ended 2025 almost where it started the year, the forex pair went through significant ups and downs. Key forces included US tariff threats, delayed monetary easing by the US Fed, and the Bank of Japan’s (BOJ) hawkish moves that pushed interest rates to their highest in three decades. The Japanese yen has had a history of dramatic turns. In the last week of January 2026, the JPY hit its lowest since July 2024,&nbsp;[plummeting to 159.5](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/01/13/yen-tumbles-on-election-bets-dollar-still-under-pressure.html)&nbsp;per dollar. Dubbed as the “Yen downward spiral,” this was no different from what the market has seen for decades. Although the Nikkei 225 jumped to record highs after Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi’s victory in the general election in February, it did little to lift the yen at the time. The forex trading community rightly questions the currency’s fate in 2026.

## **What to Expect**

As of mid-February, there are conflicting views on what to expect from the currency of the Land of the Rising Sun.

### **Strong Bearish Forecasts**

There are concerns that Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi’s reflationist policies might further weigh on the Japanese yen. Analysts at JPMorgan Chase believe that the JPY could&nbsp;[weaken to 160](https://sg.finance.yahoo.com/news/yen-bearish-voices-build-2026-153926993.html)&nbsp;or more by the end of 2026. The primary drivers of the bearish forecasts are wide yield gaps between the greenback and the yen, negative real rates in the country and ongoing capital exodus.

### **Bulls Too Have Their Case**

Fitch Ratings expects the Japanese yen to&nbsp;[appreciate by about 6%](https://www.fitchratings.com/research/sovereigns/yen-expected-to-recover-moderately-from-historical-lows-12-01-2026)&nbsp;against the dollar. This is the largest expected uptick among all Fitch-20 currencies in 2026. Nomura experts claim that a “strong LDP momentum and a risk of a super majority” may drive demand for the JPY, supporting the currency’s valuation. Bulls also consider the potential for a narrowing policy gap, which may hurt the yield advantage that the greenback enjoys. This is because the Fed may lower interest rates, while the BOJ hinted at further monetary tightening. The BOJ has also hinted toward yen-buying, which may catch short-sellers off-guard, driving the currency higher.

In an environment of high uncertainty and volatility, traders often explore forex trading opportunities via CFDs. This is because CFDs are derivative instruments that allow you to capture opportunities during both rising and falling market phases.

## **Trading USD/JPY? Add These to Your Watchlist**

Forex traders who plan to explore the Gopher (nickname for USD/JPY) in 2026 need to keep an eye on the factors set to move the currency pair:

### **Yield Gap: US Treasury vs. Japanese Government Bond**&nbsp;

Historically, if the gap between 10-year US Treasury yields and Japanese government bond (JGB) yields widens, the USD/JPY surges. Conversely, if the gap narrows, the Gopher declines.

### **Japanese Ministry of Finance (MoF) Moves**

The Japanese MoF is vigilant of yen depreciation. It may intervene if the forex pair surpasses 160. Staying on the lookout for comments from officials or minutes of meetings may shed some light on what to expect and how to refine your USD/JPY trading strategy.

### **US Economic Data**

Being the stronger currency in the pair, sentiment towards the USD has an outsized impact on the pair. Economic data releases, such as the NFP and inflation data or CPI, influence Fed interest rate decisions. Sticky inflation and strong job creation numbers may force the Fed to remain hawkish for longer. Higher interest rates tend to support the USD.

### **Global Risk Sentiment**

The USD enjoys a safe-haven status. Geopolitical tensions, supply chain risks and market crashes lead to a surge in demand for the greenback. This may weigh on the USD/JPY as investors rush to buy the US dollar.

### **The New York Rate Check**

In the last week of January 2026, the Fed conducted a rate check on the USD/JPY pair, indicating that the Trump administration also did not want Japan’s currency to steeply decline. This signals a potential joint intervention in the future against sharp JPY declines. This could also mean a ceiling of 160 for the pair. Yet, given the global push for de-dollarisation, Washington may not be keen on any intervention that involves direct dollar-selling.

## **Forex Trading Strategies for USD/JPY**

Here are a few setups to help you prepare to explore the USD/JPY:

### **Yield Spread Mean Reversion**

Historically, if the USD/JPY moves too far away from what the bond market suggests, it eventually retracts. Traders compare the USD/JPY price to the spread between the US 10Y and Japan 10Y yields. When the price makes new highs, while the yield spread declines, it is a diversion. This is considered a signal to sell as the rally loses momentum and slowly fades.

### **Trend Following**

Despite the BOJ’s tightening to 0.75%, the interest rate differential continues to favour the USD. A crossover of the 50-day and 200-day exponential moving averages (EMAs) on the daily charts may signal trend strength. Traders tend to wait for a price dip while the 50-day EMA stays above the 200-day EMA to buy.

### **Carry Trading**

Carry traders benefit from the yen’s decline against the USD, despite higher BOJ interest rates. The JPY has long been used for carry trading. In this forex trading strategy, traders borrow the currency with lower interest rates to buy one with higher rates. They aim to pocket the interest-rate differential on returning the borrowed capital with interest.

## **Summary**

- Forecasts on the performance of the USD/JPY in 2026 are divergent.
- Reflationist administrative policies could fuel yen weakness.
- If the yield gaps narrow, the USD may lose its attractiveness against the Japanese yen.&nbsp;
- Monitoring the Japanese MoF’s intervention plans could help forex traders gain insight into potential gopher movements.
- High-impact US data, such as the NFP and CPI, could offer insights into Fed decisions and USD demand.

